1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,250
Listening to people provides definite ideas for making the product more saleable.

2
00:00:05,440 --> 00:00:12,290
It also suggests to the manufacturer what he should tell consumers about the product in his advertising.

3
00:00:12,640 --> 00:00:18,050
The procedure for developing successful products is to get as much opinion as you can,

4
00:00:18,240 --> 00:00:25,170
listen to the people who will buy the product, and then design the product and its promotion to please these people.

5
00:00:25,520 --> 00:00:32,369
In an office recently, I noticed a sign that said, To sell John Brown what John Brown buys,

6
00:00:32,480 --> 00:00:35,810
you've got to see things through John Brown's eyes.

7
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:41,409
And the way to get John Brown's vision is to listen to what John Brown has to say.

8
00:00:42,480 --> 00:00:45,250
Your ears are your intake valves.

9
00:00:45,359 --> 00:00:50,690
They feed your mind raw materials that can be converted into creative power.

10
00:00:50,960 --> 00:00:57,409
We learn nothing from telling, but there is no limit to what we can learn by asking and listening.

11
00:00:58,400 --> 00:01:04,609
Try this three-stage program to strengthen your creativity through asking and listening.

12
00:01:05,920 --> 00:01:06,530
1.

13
00:01:06,800 --> 00:01:08,930
Encourage others to talk.

14
00:01:09,039 --> 00:01:14,689
In personal conversation or in group meetings, draw out people with little urges,

15
00:01:14,800 --> 00:01:20,050
such as, tell me about your experience, or what do you think should be done about,

16
00:01:20,320 --> 00:01:23,169
or what do you think is the key point.

17
00:01:23,519 --> 00:01:27,729
Encourage others to talk, and you win a double-barreled victory.

18
00:01:27,919 --> 00:01:34,050
Your mind soaks up raw material that you can use to produce creative thought, and you win friends.

19
00:01:34,399 --> 00:01:39,970
There is no surer way to get people to like you than to encourage them to talk to you.

20
00:01:40,159 --> 00:01:42,370
2.

21
00:01:42,639 --> 00:01:45,729
Test your own views in the form of questions.

22
00:01:45,999 --> 00:01:49,649
Let other people help you smooth and polish your ideas.

23
00:01:49,919 --> 00:01:53,410
Use the what-do-you-think-of-this-suggestion approach.

24
00:01:53,439 --> 00:01:54,930
Don't be dogmatic.

25
00:01:55,119 --> 00:01:59,810
Don't announce a fresh idea as if it were handed down on a gold tablet.

26
00:01:59,919 --> 00:02:02,450
Do a little informal research first.

27
00:02:02,639 --> 00:02:05,090
See how your associates react to it.

28
00:02:05,199 --> 00:02:09,330
If you do, chances are you'll end up with a better idea.

29
00:02:09,519 --> 00:02:11,169
3.

30
00:02:11,439 --> 00:02:14,129
Concentrate on what the other person says.

31
00:02:14,399 --> 00:02:17,810
Listening is more than just keeping your own mouth shut.

32
00:02:17,999 --> 00:02:21,570
Listening means letting what's said penetrate your mind.

33
00:02:21,919 --> 00:02:25,970
So often, people pretend to listen when they aren't listening at all.

34
00:02:26,159 --> 00:02:31,249
They're just waiting for the other person to pause so they can take over with the talking.

35
00:02:31,439 --> 00:02:34,050
Concentrate on what the other person says.

36
00:02:34,239 --> 00:02:35,249
Evaluate it.

37
00:02:35,519 --> 00:02:38,209
That's how you collect mind food.

